1
00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:05,749
[Ian] And also this story, this one does divide
the room somewhat. A one-off wealth tax

2
00:00:05,759 --> 00:00:09,910
will be the best way to patch up
UK public finances, battered by the

3
00:00:09,920 --> 00:00:12,470
coronavirus crisis. This is according to
the Wealth

4
00:00:12,480 --> 00:00:17,430
Tax Commission. They said the government
should look at a tax on millionaire
couples,

5
00:00:17,440 --> 00:00:21,590
rather than increasing income tax or VAT.
Taxing those households

6
00:00:21,600 --> 00:00:26,790
an extra one percent above a one million
pound threshold

7
00:00:26,800 --> 00:00:32,309
would raise £260 billion over five years.
Let's speak to Gary Stevenson,

8
00:00:32,319 --> 00:00:37,910
himself a millionaire, former trader,
wants the wealthy to pay for COVID. Now,
an inequality...

9
00:00:37,920 --> 00:00:43,590
is that right, an inequality economist?

[Gary] Yes, that's right, yeah.

10
00:00:43,600 --> 00:00:48,150
[Ian] Afternoon, Gary. The only reason I
paused at that — I thought you were
championing inequality for a second.

11
00:00:48,160 --> 00:00:53,750
That would be a curious job to have,
wouldn't it? But you're an economist
looking at issues of inequality,

12
00:00:53,760 --> 00:01:00,310
and I said at the beginning of this,
Gary, or just before the news, this one
divides me somewhat, and I'm sure

13
00:01:00,320 --> 00:01:04,789
lots of people feel the same, because I
can see how persuasive and seductive the
argument is.

14
00:01:04,799 --> 00:01:08,630
You know, if somebody is worth a few
quid, it's a one-off tax, then, you know,
why not?

15
00:01:08,640 --> 00:01:12,710
It's not going to be forever. You could
argue it's in their interest as well,
long-term.

16
00:01:12,720 --> 00:01:18,870
But there's another part of it: I think,
well, if you always go cap in hand to
rich people, you could play that game

17
00:01:18,880 --> 00:01:24,070
every day of the week that there's any
kind of crisis.

18
00:01:24,080 --> 00:01:27,270
[Gary] Yeah, that's the concern. It's
addressed in the report. A lot of the...

19
00:01:27,280 --> 00:01:32,310
some economists at the London School of
Economics and a group of lawyers and tax
accountants have looked at this.

20
00:01:32,320 --> 00:01:38,710
Yeah, they've addressed that in the
report. I think the thing we need to
consider here is there's a massive
increase, as everybody knows, in
government debt due to the covid crisis.

21
00:01:38,720 --> 00:01:44,630
It's coming up to half a trillion pounds
just from this year. Something has to be
done about that. It will have to be
addressed.

22
00:01:44,640 --> 00:01:51,749
At the moment, the very richest in our
society often pay the lowest rates of
tax. You know, it's famous, some
billionaires pay less than their
cleaners...

23
00:01:51,759 --> 00:01:56,310
[Ian] As a rate, yes.

[Gary] Yes, as a rate, yeah. Someone's gonna
have to deal with this, and if it's not
the very richest, who often pay very
little,

24
00:01:56,320 --> 00:02:00,230
then it might have to be hard-working
people like you and I.

25
00:02:00,240 --> 00:02:09,029
[Ian] I mean, in terms of tax
thresholds... I mean, you will know a bit
about this, Gary, you've done well in the
City and you've earned a few quid, and
that's fabulous.

26
00:02:09,039 --> 00:02:14,390
What happens in terms of taxation once
you... what is the top rate of tax you
can pay at that level?

27
00:02:14,400 --> 00:02:22,229
[Gary] Well, I think the top rate of income
tax at the moment is 45%.

[Ian] So that doesn't change between having,
you know, £150,000 or £50,000 to having
two billion.

28
00:02:22,239 --> 00:02:26,390
[Gary] No, well when I was working, there
was temporarily a 50% rate tax.

29
00:02:26,400 --> 00:02:30,790
[Ian] That's right.

[Gary] But I think at the moment, the top
rate is back down to 45%.

[Ian] So it's still 45%, there's nothing
above that.

30
00:02:30,800 --> 00:02:37,750
[Gary] Yeah, but what's important to realise
is that tax gets charged on worked
income. But the very richest people, they
make a lot of their income,

31
00:02:37,760 --> 00:02:44,070
often most of their income in the case of
the richest, in ways that is not through
working. For example, trusts,
inheritances, capital gains.

32
00:02:44,080 --> 00:02:49,430
And these methods of income are taxed
often a lot less, and some of these guys
will be paying less than 20% tax

33
00:02:49,440 --> 00:02:54,710
and they may even be making billions in
income.

34
00:02:54,720 --> 00:03:03,670
[Ian] Yeah.

[Gary] So there comes a question where
you have to ask, why are people who are
earning £50,000, £60,000 a year paying
45%, when the Duke of Westminster's
making nine billion pounds and not paying
anything?

35
00:03:03,680 --> 00:03:07,350
[Ian] Yeah, and in terms of your own situation,
I mean, you've done well, I don't think
you're making nine billion quid, Gary.

36
00:03:07,360 --> 00:03:10,949
But nonetheless, you would be prepared to
pay more?

37
00:03:10,959 --> 00:03:18,710
[Gary] I'll tell you what. At the moment, in
this country we've got a Chancellor whose
father-in-law is a multi-billionaire, and
his wife is estimated to be worth about
half a billion pounds.

38
00:03:18,720 --> 00:03:25,030
If Rishi Sunak pays, I'll pay.

39
00:03:25,040 --> 00:03:30,400
[Ian] But then Rishi Sunak might say, "Well,
okay, that's all very well, but he
shouldn't be judged on his spouse and her
family."

40
00:03:30,400 --> 00:03:35,360
[Gary] Alright, if Rishi Sunak's wife pays.

41
00:03:35,360 --> 00:03:39,110
[Ian] He's a self-made man. Yeah, okay, if
Mrs Sunak pays, pays the big bundle, then
you will as well?

42
00:03:39,120 --> 00:03:45,430
[Ian] How would you... I mean, would you
just have a one-off payment? Do you think
that would work? Or do you think there
should be

43
00:03:45,440 --> 00:03:49,429
an increase in the basic rates of income
tax? Because the smart money always says,
Gary, as you know,

44
00:03:49,439 --> 00:03:53,760
that if you up it to 50%, and I believe
there is evidence for this when Gordon
Brown had his sort of five minutes at the
50% rate,

45
00:03:53,760 --> 00:03:58,869
this is just income tax, that the intake
was actually... the overall tax intake was
slightly less, because people just found
ways to avoid it.

46
00:03:58,879 --> 00:04:04,149
[Gary] You know, I really want to try and
be clear about drawing the line here.
There's a difference here between...

47
00:04:04,159 --> 00:04:10,080
what these guys are doing in this report
is they're talking about taxing wealth.
So it's maybe families that have... they
might have accumulated wealth over
possibly centuries, you know,

48
00:04:10,080 --> 00:04:15,030
£50 million, £100 million. It's about
taxing families that are accumulating
huge amounts of wealth, and their wealth
is just getting bigger and bigger.

49
00:04:15,040 --> 00:04:21,759
They often don't pay income tax because
they don't get their income through
working, like you do, or like I did when
I was working.

50
00:04:21,759 --> 00:04:27,029
So we're not talking about taxing lawyers
and doctors here. We're talking about
taxing extremely wealthy families who are
accumulating wealth over generations

51
00:04:27,039 --> 00:04:33,670
and often don't get their income through
work. So it's not really about what level
of income tax; it's about, do we get the
super, super rich to pay at all? Because
often, right now, they're not paying at
all.

52
00:04:33,680 --> 00:04:39,990
[Ian] So it's a kind of misnomer really,
the idea that

53
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:45,110
we talk about income tax and we kind of
obsess on that, but actually the real big
bunce comes from elsewhere.

54
00:04:45,120 --> 00:04:49,110
It comes from those funds, those pots,
those investments, it's those kind of
areas.

55
00:04:49,120 --> 00:04:52,479
[Gary] Yeah, it's a choice, in a way, because,
you know, there's a massive debt here,
it's increasingly huge, somebody has to
pay it.

56
00:04:52,479 --> 00:04:56,400
And in a sense, the government has to
choose: do we go to the super-rich, like
for example the Chancellor's wife,

57
00:04:56,400 --> 00:05:01,110
or do we go to people who are working?

[Ian] Yeah.

[Gary] And at the moment, I've worked, and I've
paid a lot of tax.

58
00:05:01,120 --> 00:05:05,670
But a lot of these guys who are a lot
richer than me, many, many, many times
richer than me, and I presume you as
well,

59
00:05:05,680 --> 00:05:10,080
are not paying anything. And it's not
fair, and it's damaging to the economy,
because if you squeeze the middle class,
then there's no spending. You know,

60
00:05:10,080 --> 00:05:16,400
Rishi Sunak's wife is not going to keep
the whole economy alive. We need to tax
the rich as well.

61
00:05:16,400 --> 00:05:22,150
[Ian] Do you think the government response
to that might... apart from ideologically
they would say it's not the right thing
to do, and we can argue that forever,

62
00:05:22,160 --> 00:05:27,670
but do you think the government might
say, "Well, we'd need to set up such a
complicated system in order to find where
all of those

63
00:05:27,680 --> 00:05:30,309
funds and investments lurk," that it would
become impossible?

64
00:05:30,319 --> 00:05:37,350
[Gary] Yeah, I mean, when you consider, as
we've said, that the Chancellor's
father-in-law is a multi-billionaire, the
government might say something like that.

65
00:05:37,360 --> 00:05:43,749
But the work that the economists and the
various people on this panel have done
today is basically saying, "Look, we've
done the work, we've shown you how you
can do it,

66
00:05:43,759 --> 00:05:49,110
we've shown you how it can work." And
there are other economists that
have done similar work, like Gabriel
Zucman.

67
00:05:49,120 --> 00:05:52,469
You know, the economists are putting the
work in to show how you can do it. We
need the government to come on board

68
00:05:52,479 --> 00:05:57,590
and say, "Look, we are committed to
making sure the richest pay as well." And
the economists will work with them. I'll
work with them for free.

69
00:05:57,600 --> 00:06:00,870
Look, if they want to call me up, I'll
work with them, I'll tell them how to do
it.

70
00:06:00,880 --> 00:06:07,199
But we need to know they're on side, and
in theory they're on board with making
sure the super-rich, like Rishi Sunak's
family, like Jacob Rees-Mogg, actually
pay their way,

71
00:06:07,199 --> 00:06:10,870
and it's not just put on the hard-working
people of this country.

72
00:06:10,870 --> 00:06:16,400
[Ian] Good work, Gary, thank you. Gary
Stevenson, former trader, himself a
millionaire, would happily pay more money

73
00:06:16,400 --> 00:06:21,199
if other people were doing it. But is it
down to the rich to fill that void?
